"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964950","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-06","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs and officials have been in touch with both Governments to express our concern over the dispute and its potential implications. We have and will continue to urge restraint and de-escalation through the appropriate diplomatic channels.</p><p>The Government continues to promote human rights across the Middle East, both bilaterally and with key international partners such as Canada. The UK frequently expresses concerns on human rights issues to Saudi Arabia at the most senior levels. We can only bring about the changes we would like to see by working with countries. We do not shy away from raising legitimate human rights concerns, and we make this point very clearly in public and in private.</p><p>The UK is a close partner to both Canada and Saudi Arabia and enjoys positive and constructive diplomatic relations with both countries. It is in the UK’s interest that we have both public and private conversations on matters of mutual concern.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-06T15:58:50.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964950/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964950/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964950/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-03","Canada and Saudi Arabia: Diplomatic Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of recent changes in diplomatic relations between Canada and Saudi Arabia on the Government's relationship with those countries.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","169162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964951","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-06","<p>​We are monitoring closely the case of Israa al-Ghomgham and other political activists. We continue to raise our concerns on human rights with the Saudi authorities in private.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-06T15:59:59.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964951/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964951/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964951/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-03","Israa al-Ghomgham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Saudi Arabian counterpart on the forthcoming trial of Israa al-Ghomgham in that country; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","169163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964952","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-09-13","<p>In our Smart Systems and Flexibility Plan, published last year, the Government committed to amending the Electricity Act 1989 to define electricity storage as a distinct subset of generation in primary legislation, when parliamentary time allows. This is an important measure to improve regulatory clarity for electricity storage, and one that we will honour.</p><p>The Plan also addressed the issue of storage operators overpaying certain levies and charges. Ofgem has consulted on a new modified generation licence for storage facilities and will respond to this consultation shortly. Storage providers that hold this licence will not pay towards certain levies (the Renewables Obligation, Feed in Tariff, Contracts for Difference and Capacity Market auctions costs). The Government has also clarified that the electricity received and stored by electricity storage facilities may be supplied to them free from the Climate Change Levy where relevant conditions are met.</p><p>Ofgem outlined in their Targeted Charging Review Consultation, their view that storage is currently overpaying network charges and stated that the industry is best placed to take forward these changes. Industry has now raised these code modifications, and these are now going through industry governance.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-09-13T15:20:09.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964952/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964952/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964952/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-09-03","Electricity: Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if the Government will bring forward legislative proposals to (a) update the definition of electricity storage and (b) tackle double charging and other regulatory disparities.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","168987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964953","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-09-11","<p>The English Housing Survey 2016-17 End User Licence household data was sent to the UK Data Service on 16/07/18. Publication of the data has been delayed because the UK Data Service is undergoing a significant upgrade to its systems, which will continue into mid-September. In the meantime, potential data users are welcome to contact the English Housing Survey team (<a href="mailto:EHS@communities.gsi.gov.uk" target="_blank">EHS@communities.gsi.gov.uk</a>) at MHCLG to request access.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-09-11T15:04:47.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964953/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964953/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964953/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-09-03","Housing: Surveys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to his Answer of 20 July 2018 to Question 163756 on Housing: Surveys, when the 2016-17 End User Licence household data will be available via the UK Data Service.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","168993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964954","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-09-06","<p>The Department does not publish Affordable Homes Programme allocations data by the financial year. Initial programme allocations to January 2017, including by Homes England operating area, can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/affordable-homes-programme-2016-to-2021-successful-bidders" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/affordable-homes-programme-2016-to-2021-successful-bidders</a></p><p>The Department does not publish funding allocation information on a local authority level basis.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2018-09-06T14:55:02.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964954/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964954/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-09-03","Affordable Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the total Homes England grant funding for affordable housing allocated by (a) Homes England operating region and (b) local authority area in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","168994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964955","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-11","<p>The recent report from the Group of Eminent Experts further underlines the deeply concerning human rights situation in Yemen and the importance of reaching a political solution to this conflict. We are carefully considering the contents of the report ahead of the upcoming session of the UN Human Rights Council.</p><p>As we have consistently, we will emphasise to all parties the vital importance of compliance with international humanitarian law, press for action to address the humanitarian crisis, and encourage all parties to engage in the UN-led political process in good faith.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-11T15:26:00.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964955/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964955/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-03","Yemen: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government plans to support the renewal of the mandate of the UN Human Rights Council group of eminent experts to investigate violations of human rights and humanitarian law in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","169638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964956","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-11","<p>The Government's legal advice is subject to legal professional privilege. The High Court’s judgment of July 2017 confirmed that we have in place a robust and rigorous process for assessing export licensing decisions for Saudi Arabia. We assess all export licensing decisions for Saudi Arabia on a case by case basis against the Consolidated Criteria. Our assessments take into account evidence from a range of sources including the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, other government departments, the media and NGO reports. ​</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-11T15:27:26.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964956/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964956/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-03","Saudi Arabia: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Attorney General on the legality of arm sales to the Saudi and Emirati-led coalition in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","169639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964957","Department for Education","false","2018-09-11","<p>The department keeps under review the use of the 16 to 19 Bursary Fund to inform our understanding of whether this is effectively supporting our most economically disadvantaged students.</p><p> </p><p>A number of other financial support schemes are available to eligible 16 to 19 year olds such as support for free meals in further education, childcare costs if needed and residential support.</p><p> </p><p>Together these are supporting young people to participate in education whatever their financial situation and have contributed to the current record high proportion of 16 to 17 year olds who are participating in education or apprenticeships, the highest since consistent records began.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-09-11T15:20:44.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964957/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964957/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-09-03","Sixth Form Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of financial support for sixth form students.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","169640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964958","Department for Education","false","2018-09-11","<p>Information on the number of teachers teaching individual subjects is available for state funded secondary schools only. Because the school workforce survey was only introduced in 2010 there is no information available for 2009. In November 2012 there was an estimated headcount of 24,700 teachers teaching PE in state funded secondary schools. In November 2017 there were 23,100.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-09-11T15:13:19.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964958/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964958/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964958/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-09-03","Physical Education: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many PE teachers were employed by schools in England in (a) 2009, (b) 2012 and (c) 2017.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","169641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964959","Department for Education","false","2018-09-11","<p>The government is clear that PE is a valuable subject. For this reason, the national curriculum continues to ensure that PE is compulsory at all four key stages. Academies and free schools are not required to follow the national curriculum but must provide a broad and balanced curriculum that should include PE. Ofsted inspections evaluate the effectiveness of the PE curriculum in all state funded schools as part of a broad and balanced curriculum.</p><p>We do not hold information on the average hours per week taught by secondary schools. Information on the number of hours taught in individual subjects has been collected since 2010 in the school workforce census for state-funded secondary schools only. This information is therefore not available for 2009. In November 2012, the number of hours taught in PE to pupils in state funded secondary schools, was 317,100 hours. For 2017, this same statistic was 282,200 hours. This school workforce census data can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-workforce" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-workforce</a>.</p><p>However, these figures do not cover the time dedicated to extra-curricular sport or other physical activity done outside of formal lessons.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-09-11T07:48:06.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964959/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964959/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-09-03","Physical Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average number of hours per week was of PE undertaken by pupils in secondary school pupils in England in (a) 2009, (b) 2012 and (c) 2017.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","169642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964960","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-09-06","<p>The Building Safety Programme has been working with local authorities and building owners across England to identify properties over 18 metres that might have potentially unsafe cladding systems, similar to Grenfell Tower.</p><p>As of 16 August, there are 159 social housing buildings that have cladding systems which the Independent Expert Panel advise are unlikely to meet current building regulations, and therefore present a fire hazard on buildings over 18 metres. Of these 159 buildings, 43 are local authority owned housing, and 101 are housing association owned. We do not hold information on any non-ACM affected buildings over 18 metres. The latest ACM testing results are in in our monthly data release, which can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/735703/Building_Safety_Data_Release_August_2018.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/735703/Building_Safety_Data_Release_August_2018.pdf</a></p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-09-06T14:54:24.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964960/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964960/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-09-03","High Rise Flats: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many of the 4,000 tall tower blocks similar to Grenfell Tower which the Government announced last year would receive emergency safety inspections measure 30 metres/10 storeys or higher and are under (a) local authority or (b) housing association control.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","169752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964961","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-11","<p>No comparative assessment of the level of child obesity in 2009 and 2017 has been made.</p><p> </p><p>Data from the Health Survey for England 2016 indicate that 15.7% of children aged 2-15 were classified as obese using population monitoring thresholds in England in 2009. 16.0% of children aged 2-15 were classified as obese in 2016. Data for 2017 data are not yet available.</p><p> </p><p>16.1% of boys aged 2-15 were classified as obese in 2009, and 15.3% of girls. In 2016 15.9% of boys aged 2-15 were classified as obese, and 16.1% of girls.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-09-11T16:01:09.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964961/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964961/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-03","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what comparative assessment he has made of the level of obesity in children in (a) 2009 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","169643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964962","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-09-11","<p>Local authorities are the single biggest investors in community sport, spending around £1 billion a year. Sport England works with a wide range of local authorities, providing expert advice and funding to sustain and increase the number of people playing sport regularly.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-09-11T15:00:48.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964962/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964962/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964962/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-09-03","Local Government Finance: Leisure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of trends in the level of Government funding for local authorities on local authority spending on sports and recreation.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","169644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964963","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-09-11","<p>Sport and physical activity in prison can help to build prisoner’s confidence, provide purposeful activity and support engagement with rehabilitation when prisoners are preparing for release. There are measures in place to monitor the effectiveness and participation levels of physical education (PE) across the prison estate, and the standards of sports and activities are monitored by Physical Education Managers (PEM). I have attached available data in relation to prisoner participation levels over the last 10 years. Unfortunately, data for 2011 – 2012 is not available.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Our response to Professor Rosie Meek's independent review of sport and physical activity sets out some of the work we are doing to improve provision of sport and physical activity education in the secure youth estate. That response can be found here: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/733311/a-sporting-chance-govt-response.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/733311/a-sporting-chance-govt-response.pdf</a>. Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service (HMPPS) also recently conducted a strategic review of PE in prisons which examined current delivery, and measured delivery effectiveness against specifications. It also considered how current PE delivery meets the needs of prisoners, staff, and the emerging requirements from prison reform initiatives. We hope to publish these findings in due course. HMPPS does not separately identify spending associated with sports programmes. The information in relation to the amount spent in 2009 and 2017 could only be obtained at disproportionate cost</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Prisoner participation levels from data available – Physical Education </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td col